description: - Provides intelligence support to 78 acquisition programs, comprising $19B in the USAF budget. - Coordinates the Intelligence Division effort to evaluate current programs and development planning (future programs) to assess intelligence efficiency and effectiveness through an Intelligence Supportability Analysis (ISA) process to support program success and the AFROC & JROC Intelligence Certification process. -Provides intelligence analysis, AF ISR expertise and SCI access for Fighter/Bomber, ISR SOF, Mobility, Tanker and Agile Combat Support Program Executive Officers (PEO) and functional directorates to execute their programs and enhance operational success. - Principle advisor to the Intelligence Director (LCMC/IN) for acquisition enterprise intelligence standardization; prepares communication to HHQ and other senior leaders. - Supervises and directs 13 Billets, managing $3.2M in annual manpower resources. Provides administrative direction in budget, plans and programs, operations, communications, intelligence, and personnel areas. - Coordinates the efforts of division engagement in ISR requirements and planning forums: Global Integrated ISR (GIISR) Core Function Master Plan (CFMP), Distributed Common Ground Station (DCGS) Requirements Review Board (DRRB), SIGINT Capabilities Working Group (SCWG) and GEOINT Capabilities Working Group (GCWG).

description: As a Training Specialist with Parsons, PGS Division, I assisted in developing TRIRIGA training in support of the Air Force NEXGEN IT ($86 mil) contract supporting over 60,000 Air Force Civil Engineers worldwide. Reviewed design documents and training requirements to draft a training outline tailored to the audience knowledge and skill level. Budget cuts forced reduction in project manning.

description: in the cryptology community I supervised 16 instructors in the guidance and management of over 400 multi-service students annually. Lesson topics taught include basic intelligence, Intelligence sources, collecting/gathering, analyzing, evaluating, and correlating information from a variety of resources, such as Imagery Intelligence (IMINT), ELINT, SIGINT, message traffic and numerous intelligence databases. This information is ultimately used in preparation for upcoming Navy deployments where students learn to calculate all the information and develop briefs given to senior personnel. Used proprietary software to develop scenarios used to simulate actual area specific training for numerous worldwide hotspots. Key ELINT subject matter expert representing Navy interests in multiple course reviews, updates, and modifications. Daily supervisory tasks include: providing instruction, test and curriculum development, staff and student management, safeguarding of classified material, encouraging discipline and adherence to Navy rules and regulations, and counseling staff and students (both positive and negative).

description: Front-line supervisor of 13-15 personnel deploying on Submarines in support of national security objectives. Extensive deployment experience with CLUSTER SNOOP, Oilstock, Automated Information System (AIS), and C2PC equipment/software. Attended Intermediate signals analyst course (Navy NEC 9141, TECHELINT) where I learned how to analyze ELINT signals in a Signals Analysis Lab (SAL). I used GALE-LITE software daily in support of functions such as SIGINT operations control, Intelligence Preparation of the Battlespace (IPB) management, and Electronic Warfare (EW). Gathered and evaluated information, using tools such as IMINT, ELINT, SIGINT and other confidential information sources to prepare Intelligence reports. One of only two designated Navy classified material couriers carrying highly classified materials across the United States and to foreign countries.

description: As a Leading Petty Officer and Master Training Specialist (MTS) in the cryptology community I supervised 22 instructors in the guidance and management of over 440 multi-service students annually. Lesson topics taught include basic intelligence, Intelligence sources, collecting/gathering, analyzing, evaluating, and correlating information from a variety of resources, such as Imagery Intelligence (IMINT), ELINT, SIGINT, message traffic and numerous intelligence databases via Gale-Lite. This information is ultimately used in preparation for upcoming Navy deployments where students learn to calculate all the information and develop briefs given to senior personnel. Used proprietary software to develop scenarios used to simulate actual area specific training for numerous worldwide hotspots. Key ELINT subject matter expert representing Navy interests in multiple course reviews, updates, and modifications. Daily supervisory tasks include: providing instruction, test and curriculum development, staff and student management, safeguarding of classified material, encouraging discipline and adherence to Navy rules and regulations, and counseling staff and students (both positive and negative). Returned in 2009 to take the program lead and requalified to the newest version of MTS.

description: Highly skilled with multiple SIGINT intelligence applications and software tools. Effective operator and frequent user of IC systems, tools, and databases for intelligence operations. Analyzed, produced, and disseminated hundreds of highly perishable information SIGINT reports. Drafted, evaluated, and performed quality controls on hundreds of intelligence product reports producing scores of AOR-based SIGINT summary and debriefs. Subject Matter Expert (SME) for DCGS-AF, distributed operations, geo-location. Analyzed time-critical intelligence information and produced SIGINT Threat Warning reports in support of U.S. assets in the assigned Area of Responsibility (AOR). Acquired, processed, identified, analyzed, and reported on electromagnetic emissions. Operated on electronic equipment and computer systems to exploit signals intelligence production efforts. Performed communication signals intelligence production and analysis, to include acquiring signals through optimum antenna manipulation and receiver tuning. Used advanced computer software programs to manipulate and extract intelligence data from electromagnetic emissions. Operated on computer terminals for data entry, query, data restructuring, and signals development. Interpreted and rendered preliminary analysis. Used analytical aids and related reference material to help identify signals and detect abnormalities. Maintained databases on various signal types and activities using computer and hard copy products. Notified appropriate personnel and work centers of unusual activities or critical situations. Direction finding (DF) within the Intelligence Surveillance Reconnaissance (ISR) platform while creating GEOINT map manipulation. •Exceptionally Qualified rating as DCGS Special Signals Operator (held by less than 2.5% of all DCGS ops). Experienced Manager overseeing, training, collection, and report dissemination activities for teams of 4-10 individuals at any given time during live missions.

description: Perform in-depth technical signals analysis on data using the latest analog and digital analysis techniques, equipment, and programs, including ASPEN, Data Assessment and Selection Service (DASS), and MARTES analysis software, to support the Scientific and Technical intelligence analysis mission at the National Ground Intelligence Center (NGIC). Consults with peer specialists as well as government customer to define the scope of very complex signals analysis projects in support of Electronic Warfare Integrated Reprogramming Database (EWIRDB). Supports government customer as an expert TECHELINT signals analyst in designing more efficient techniques and investigate work for dealing with typical TECHELINT signals analysis problem areas. Develops and applies new analytical methods to identify and improve TECHELINT signal analysis techniques to validate Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) analysis problem areas. Conduct research of automated technical data using Generic Area Limitation Environment-Lite (GALE-Lite), and WRANGLER applications, as well as compiling all source information for inclusion in and production of technical analysis reports. Knowledgeable of intelligence processes, cycle, and organizations with in-depth experience of systems, procedures, and methods of collecting, analyzing, compiling, reporting, and disseminating intelligence data.

summary: 14 years experience in the Intelligence community conducting signals analysis and reporting. SUMMARY OF QUALIFICATIONS •Top Secret/SCI Clearance, exp. 2017. CI Polygraph conducted June 2009. •14 years analytical experience as a Signal/Intelligence Analyst with the United States Army, Lockheed Martin Corporation, L3 STRATIS, and Northrop Grumman. EXPERIENCE Analysis •Certified on 5 real time systems conducting analog and digital signal processing. •Provided over 300 time sensitive reports for national level consumers. •Proficient in use of computer applications, intelligence software, and hardware tools: Microsoft Office, LINUX, UNIX, XBIT, MARTES, BLACKMAGIC, Wave and Data Viewer Tools, ORQAM, User Interface System, OILSTOCK, Spectrum Analyzers, Oscilloscopes, Receivers, Frequency Counters, and Demodulators. Leadership and Interpersonal Skills •Experienced and skilled in providing briefings to superiors and effective instruction, training, and directions to subordinates in support of Intelligence Collection. •Supervised in 3 signal development centers supporting a 24/7 watch. •Served as Army Liaison and Mentoring officer at Communications and Signals course; writing student reports, handling issues, and providing academic assistance. Training •Certified Senior Joint Service School Instructor for Basic Communication Signals course. •Trained over 300 students and 4 classes with a GPA 3% above course average. •Certified 11 analysts on real time analog and digital signal collection positions. EDUCATION •B.A. Intelligence Studies GPA 3.77, American Military University August 2012 •A.A.S. Intelligence Operations GPA 4.0, Cochise College, AZ May 2009 •U.S. Army: Intermediate Communication Signals Analysis Course, Journeyman Instructor Training, Primary leadership Course, Advanced Communication Intelligence (COMINT) Mapping, Basic COMINT Mapping, Basic Communication Signals Course.

summary: CLEARANCE: Current TS//SCI AUG2012 with CI Poly JAN2013 Well-versed, disciplined, and talented Signals Analyst with expansive interpersonal skills and strong personnel management capabilities. Over ten years of TechELINT analysis and over two years of TechELINT Instructor experience. Three years experience training and developing operational capabilities to conduct cyberspace operations and information operations (IO). Broad Intelligence background includes SIGINT reporting, analysis, dissemination, operations management, and training. Scope of experience demonstrates ability to adapt to complex fluid operational environments, manage multiple personnel, simultaneously plan and manage complex projects or systems, identify and allocate resources to optimize mission execution, and present sound and reasoned operational approaches to implement strategic vision. Extensive experience working within DoD, Intelligence Community, Joint and Service staff, and foreign agencies. LEADERSHIP HIGHLIGHTS -Program Development: Provided direction, insight, and leadership in developing only Army SIGINT customer engagement mission within a national level program. Emulated mission after other military partners. Further Integrated engagement mission into larger corporation. - Operational Efficiency: Developed, implemented, and managed the plans, procedures, and functions of two new HR offices Ensured all the organizational HR actions were seamlessly transferred, maintained, and completed - Personnel Management: Focused on personnel development. A diverse manager of resources. Developed, implemented, and facilitated over 300 hours of unique and technical mission essential training ensuring unparalleled expertise on the battlefield.

description: Direct the daily operations of the only Army operated 24/7 mission for National Security Agency-Colorado (NSA-C). The TCE provides SIGINT support to deployed entities worldwide. Support is provided utilizing a strong foundation of networking, operator training, and operator competence. Supervise 22 joint service personnel through daily communications, direction and guidance, monthly and quarterly evaluations, counseling, mentoring, operations log, and, conflict resolution. Plan, coordinate and execute all training strategies and operational functions. Establish and implement policies, goals, objectives, and procedures through continued job training, weekly meetings, evaluations, and constantly evolving priorities. Liaise with deploying and deployed units, at all echelons, to mitigate intelligence gaps. Provide Combatant Commands and Theater-level programs access to National level resources through multiple communications mediums and classifications to include emails, chat, websites, telephone conference, and databases. Direct and execute daily research, utilizing multiple sources, on political, military, economic and industrial forces in various regions of the world, as well as foreign intelligence threat entities, DoD, and U.S. resources. Disseminate information to multiple personnel in support of operations. Complete Quarterly updates of formal training ensuring relevancy of training based on war fighter needs. Engage all resources, internal and external to the NSA-C, in an effort to gather and disseminate all pertinent intelligence through networking and collaboration. Conduct bi-weekly meetings with senior leadership discussing personnel and equipment requirement and rotations. Regularly asked to brief high level personnel both in person and through video teleconference. Gather facts and use effective analytical and evaluative methods to accurately assess information and make sound decisions.

summary: CLEARANCE: Current TS//SCI AUG2012 with CI Poly JAN2013 Well-versed, disciplined, and talented Signals Analyst with expansive interpersonal skills and strong personnel management capabilities. Over ten years of TechELINT analysis and over two years of TechELINT Instructor experience. Three years experience training and developing operational capabilities to conduct cyberspace operations and information operations (IO). Broad Intelligence background includes SIGINT reporting, analysis, dissemination, operations management, and training. Scope of experience demonstrates ability to adapt to complex fluid operational environments, manage multiple personnel, simultaneously plan and manage complex projects or systems, identify and allocate resources to optimize mission execution, and present sound and reasoned operational approaches to implement strategic vision. Extensive experience working within DoD, Intelligence Community, Joint and Service staff, and foreign agencies. LEADERSHIP HIGHLIGHTS -Program Development: Provided direction, insight, and leadership in developing only Army SIGINT customer engagement mission within a national level program. Emulated mission after other military partners. Further Integrated engagement mission into larger corporation. - Operational Efficiency: Developed, implemented, and managed the plans, procedures, and functions of two new HR offices Ensured all the organizational HR actions were seamlessly transferred, maintained, and completed - Personnel Management: Focused on personnel development. A diverse manager of resources. Developed, implemented, and facilitated over 300 hours of unique and technical mission essential training ensuring unparalleled expertise on the battlefield.

description: Responded to, utilizing multiple tools, databases, and analysis techniques, National level tasking and intelligence needs to fulfill Intelligence Community SIGINT requirements. Directed the daily operations of 15 Army personnel working within 3 different work sections. Conducted in-depth analysis on several Signals of Interest (SOIs), resulting in the release of multiple reports documenting first use, system upgrades, and proliferation. Operated a variety of electronic equipment integrated in a single console or part of an overall system. Applied electronic measurement techniques and identified complex waveforms, pulse trains and various forms of modulation. Considered a subject matter expert by peers. Networked and collaborated with multiple national level organizations in support of national requirements. Applied facts and estimates to solve problems. Instructed 32 personnel on NSA analysis trends and skills. Followed established reporting procedures and protocols. Thorough knowledge of intelligence community policies, entities, missions, resources, operations, capabilities, databases and requirements. Mentored new personnel. Completed four six to eight month tours of different work sections. Each section was responsible for different missions within the intelligence community. Completed advanced analysis projects while assigned to each section. Gathered facts and used effective analytical and evaluative methods to accurately assess information and make sound decisions Competently performed intelligence research and analysis on the employment, force structure, production, and technical capabilities of foreign adversary networks and exploitation threat systems. Communicated effectively with others, both orally and in writing, in working out solutions to problems or questions relating to policies.

description: Systems operator within a Special Access Program (SAP) that was the Army’s only Network Warfare Battalion (ANWB). Managed 30 Personnel. Directed the training, testing, utilization, and deployment of equipment, tools, and personnel in support of organization’s requirements. Supported Computer Network Operations (CNO), Information Operations (IO), and SIGINT capabilities development, mission planning, policy development, and operations execution of assigned missions. Directed the planning, training, and execution of numerous successful operational deployments resulting in mission successes recognized by multiple high level commanders. Reviewed resource planning procedures and regulations in support of completing a variety of program and requirement-related tasks Supported and advised the Army’s Combat developer in research, development, and fielding of sensitive IO equipment for conducting unconventional operations ISO national, joint, and Army requirements. Evaluated Intelligence Community policies, entities, functions, missions, resources, operations, capabilities, databases, and requirements to perform intelligence research and analysis on the employment, force structure, production, and technical capabilities of foreign adversary networks and exploitation threat systems. Managed logistics for a platoon sized element of military and civilian personnel to perform first test in three years of SAP equipment. Served as Chief of Training for ANWB and responsible for command members training needs and records management. Facilitated hours of technical mission training. Selected for Two multi-month TDY’s in support of unit’s mission requirements and technical needs. Army Intelligence representative to numerous joint and inter-agency working groups. Facilitated the unconventional training, preparation, and deployment of the Army’s 1st and 2nd Computer Network Operations team. One of 1st certified operators on unique Army system.

description: Managed Seven Military and Civilian operators. Operated electronic analysis and processing equipment in support of SIGINT mission requirements. Conducted 1st line technical analysis and reporting on hundreds of Signals of Interest (SOIs). Correlated operating parameters to weapons systems and disseminated findings to the Intelligence Community and National databases. Performed pulse level analysis to determine interpulse and intrapulse modulation, scan, frequency agility, and potential time shared multiplexing for new and unusual signals of interest. Operated a variety of electronic equipment integrated into a single console or part of an overall system. Applied electronic measurement techniques and identified complex waveforms, pulse trains and various forms of modulation. Considered a subject matter expert by peers. Conduct computer systems planning and database management for intelligence systems. Researched, utilizing multiple sources, political, military, economic, industrial forces in various regions of the world, as well as foreign intelligence threat entities, DoD, and U.S. resources. Gathered facts and used effective analytical and evaluative methods to accurately assess information and make sound decisions. Disseminated information to personnel in support of operations. Instructed personnel on intelligence community policies, entities, missions, resources, operations, capabilities, databases and requirements. Developed strong knowledge of the capabilities of Combat Air Forces, Special Operations and Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance platforms and Air Operations Center structure, relationships, mission and responsibilities. Identified strategies to better support data identification and reporting techniques to information production elements and operators. Developed training material and trained numerous operators; tested system updates and modifications and forwarded findings to developer.

description: My purpose as a Naval Junior Reserve Officer Training Corps NJROTC is to instill in the students at Dundalk High School a secondary educational institutions the values of citizenship, service to the United States, and personal responsibility and a sense of accomplishment."Some additional objectives that Cadets can establish..... - Developing citizenship and patriotism - Developing self-reliance and responsiveness to all authority. - Improving the ability to communicate well both orally and in writing. - Developing an appreciation of the importance of physical fitness. - Increasing a respect for the role of the U.S. Armed Forces in support of national objectives. - Developing a knowledge of team building skills and basic military skills. - Taking 3–4 years of the course grants cadets the ability to rank higher if they pursue a military career. Also I instill meaningful leadership instruction of benefit to the student and it's value to the Armed Forces.

summary: Fourteen years of quality performance as an Intelligence Professional. Proven track record in specific areas of expertise to include signals intelligence, signals analysis, maintains Tactical EA-6b Mission Support (TEAMS) database, Logistics, builds mission and routes, perform post-flight analysis, and counter-intelligence. Operational knowledge of threat analysis, operational assessments, and the following related systems: AN/ASQ-142, AN/ULQ-16, SLQ-32, Specific Emitter Identification (SEI), Signal generators, graphic recorders, Spectrum Analyzer, and a number of intelligence community tools and databases. I possess a comprehensive knowledge of clearance administration, Mission Reporting (MISREP), ELINT, minor computer repairs, networking and maintaining logs and records files. Highly organized and dependable with a pleasant personality that sincerely enjoys working with people.

description: 1. Performs any variety of sales and customer services at a retail window such as maintaining sufficient inventory of and selling stamps, stamped paper, other retail products and services and may use a computerized system, accepting and delivering packages and accountable mail; issuing and cashing foreign and domestic postal money orders; accepting and responding to customer claims and inquiries, and providing information to the public regarding postal regulations. 2. Provides sales and customer service support by greeting customers and explaining store layout; determining special interests and referring to sales and promotional programs; offers assistance in product selection; provides special assistance; and answers customer inquiries when needed. 3. Provides product and service information to customers, including informing customers regarding special offers; suggestive selling related merchandise; promoting products based on customer needs. Provides additional information regarding product features and services. 4. Handles and processes customer purchases and returns relating to products and services and may use a point of sale system. Assists customers with transactions. 5. Maintains appearance of store by setting up, arranging, and replenishing displays and merchandise racks; ensures display and selling areas, work stations, and storage areas are presentable to customers. 6. Conducts product inventories by counting items on hand; attaches and removes security devices; accounts for items on display; and verifies and records sales floor inventory and shrinkage. Brings inventory discrepancies and shrinkage reports to the attention of the appropriate supervisory presence. 7. Performs other duties as assigned.

description: Open Source Intelligence (OSINT) Desk Officer for NTOC. - Support a high tempo mission on 24/7 computer network operation (CNO) floor in charge of defending the .mil infrastructure. - Responded to cyber targets development request from SIGINT Intrusion Analyst and MALWARE Analysts. - Responded to Senior US government intelligence and CNO officials request for information (RFI) on targets of interest (TOI). description: - The TSSC Desk Officer. The focal point for issues relating to the TechSIGINT disciplines (ELINT, FISINT, RF communication Internal & External, Performa, and Specific Emitter Identification). Assists NSOC Senior Operation Officer (SOO) in monitoring targets and threats and keep various NSA/SIGINT enterprise partners apprised of advances and capabilities of weapon threats and space technology. Knowledgeable in the use of more than several analytical tools to provide assessments to the Director of NSA (DIRNSA) and the Senior Operation Officer (SOO). Recipient of two Star awards and a Letter of Appreciation (LOA) from Director NSA/CSS Colorado. - Expertly filtered and disseminated mission-relevant Technical SIGINT information from multiple databases to the Senior Operation Officer in NSOC and extended enterprise and created SOPs for new desk officers. - Provided timely mapping, graphics, and plots to Senior Operation Officer to assist in the understanding of the real-world threat and scenarios. Provided quality control over all classified information - In role a senior non-commissioned officer, managed personnel, conducted performance evaluations, communicated information to senior leadership. - NSA Point-of Entry for all Weapon & Space (W&S) customers, partners and intelligence stake holders. I have reviewed thousands of messages to create Global Technical SIGINT Enterprise Items of Interest (IOI). During heighten posture I have assisted SIGINT enterprise in Counterterrorism operations, tracked high interest targets and adjusted national tasking posture for numerous major W&S events to ensure collection of high value targets. - Liaison between NSOC and Defense Special Missile and Aerospace Center (DEFSMAC) and responsible for the creation of numerous Windshield Articles. The articles are accessed by a number of SIGINT enterprise personnel. Briefed the Extended Enterprise during the daily Back-row briefings on occasion on behalf of the DEFSMAC.

description: - Tactical Expert. Supervised and evaluated 10 Sailors. As Combat System Training Team (CSTT) Tactical member for Electronic Warfare (EW) area. Trained and evaluated four Sailors in support of 13 integrated team events during a highly compressed inter-deployment training cycle earning a score of 88% during ULTRA-C. During our tour through Second, Fifth, Sixth and Seventh Fleet EWs manually generated over hundreds of TACELINT messages earning recognition from Fleet Commander Admiral and SPAWAR. -Performed a variety of specialized duties associated with the collection and processing of airborne, ship borne, and land-based Radio Detecting and Ranging (RADAR) signals. I operated electronic intelligence receiving and direction system, digital recording devices, analysis terminals, and associated computer equipment. The systems I operated produced high-powered jamming signals used to deceive electronic sensors and defeat radar guided weapons system. -Develops Electronic Order of Battle (EOB) in support of local area, fleet, and joint fleet operations. Provided the human interface between electronic warfare equipment, both active and passive, and other shipboard weapons systems related to integration under the Combat Weapons System Organization. Served as staff advisory in the employment of electronic warfare equipment involving surface, subsurface, air and satellite forces. Provided resident expertise for the collection of intelligence data related to enemy use of any portion of the electromagnetic spectrum. - Electronic Intelligence (ELINT) in accordance with fleet and national tasking; provided safety of platform, Indications and Warning (I & W), and Anti-Ship Missile Defense (ASMD); and provided technical and tactical guidance to Warfare Commanders and national consumers in support of surface, subsurface, air, and special warfare operations.

description: - Leading Petty Officer (LPO). Supervised 1195 man-hours of topside preservation on the SRBOC deck, six MK-137 launcher, I aided and lead another ship with 270 hours of corrective maintenance on their SLQ-32 and Decoy System. My attention to detail earned my ship praise from both Afloat Training Group (ATG) Mayport and the other ship Captain. Also was responsible for getting the ship equipped for Ballistic Missile Defense (BDM) and everyone trained and ready to go on 2010 deployment. - Quality Assurance Supervisor. Train and supervise QAIs, Cleanliness Inspectors/Certifiers, and other personnel, involved in controlled work, in the performance of their QA duties. - Quality Assurance Inspector. Verify QA forms are filled out correctly and attached to items removed from a controlled system for transfer to another Fleet activity and ensure items received from another ship or activity have QA forms tags attached.. Inspected all work making sure it met the minimum requirements set forth in latest applicable plans, specifications and directives of higher authority as stated in the FWP. - Safety Inspector. Out of numerous safety inspections I tracked, identified, and corrected over 75 safety violations making the ship a safer working and living environment. Safety observer three live firing exercises and complete two weapons on load and offload with zero incidents.

description: - Command Indoctrination Coordinator. As new Sailors checked onboard I was in charge of showing them the first 72 hour video and making sure they were enrolled in Indoctrination Division (I-Division). I coordinated with 27 other instructors and facilitators ranging from E-6 and above to create an indoctrination schedule of 49 topics once a quarter. My direct efforts set a positive tone for 163 new Sailors. This helped increase their knowledge and familiarization about the ship, Operational Risk Management (ORM), Passive Countermeasure System (PCMS), Mentoring Program, Alcohol and Drug Abuse Managers/Supervisor (ADAMS), and Navy Rights and Responsibility (NR&R). - Combat System Training Team (CSTT). Was the Leading Petty Officer (LPO) of the Electronic Warfare (EW) shop and member of the CSTT team. Built scenarios with Battle Electronic Warfare Training (BEWT), helped trained and evaluated five Sailors of integrated team events, received an 88% during ULTRA-C. The training that was provided helped during sortie with a crew of 137 members and only two EW personnel including myself.

Monthly I would coordinate with the 5-8 ships that were in port; each ship would send several EW’s to the training we provided at ATG They would work on external and internal voice communication procedures, MK53 decoy launching system deployment, and AN/SLQ-32A threat recognition and identification. Trained 13 sailors and assessed four Navy ships in Information Warfare (IW) tactics and administrative procedures. Assessed two integral warfare areas ensuring 29 continuous certification requirements were met and accelerated certification for immediate fleet tasking.

description: - Supervised and evaluated 15 Sailors. Responsible for signals recognition training for basic and advance SOPs. Identified and analyzed complex and sophisticated radio signals, managed computer networks operations, and performed system analysis to ensure effective data flow and prepared technical reports. Collected, analyzed, exploited, and disseminated Electronic Intelligence (ELINT) in accordance with fleet and national tasking and indication and warning (I&W), Anti-Ship Missile Defense (ASMD); and provided technical and tactical guidance to Warfare Commanders and National consumers in report of surface, subsurface, air, and special warfare operations. Designed and implemented a comprehensive command training database that tracked job qualifications. - Electronic Warfare – Training Group Center (EW-TGC): I provided TechELINT and OpELINT training to VQ-1, VAQ, and PACOMNORWEST waterfront CTTs, CTRs, ATs, ISs, and EWs. This analytical skill training resulted in a higher level of intelligences information being provided to the customer. I was responsible for classified information and multi-million dollar Signal Analyst Lab (SAL) equipment in EW-TGC spaces. Equipment operated or qualified to operate: Gale-Lite, Martes, SEI, PASS, MATT, TEAMS, Wrangler/Wing, all signals related analog/ digital, and analysis equipment. -Fleet Training. Responsible for scheduling and coordinating all courses given to PACNORWEST Afloat Units. As the Course Curriculum Model Manager (CCMM) I had the authority to maintain, develop, and revise courses using CeTARS and STM. - Web-Site Designer. As Leader of four Command Web Administrators I devoting over 587 hours restructuring EW-TGC web page to Fleet Training and Navy Information Operation Command (NIOC). Also maintaining the command internet and intranet home pages to make sure that fleet we support is up to date in what we could provide. In return this helps everyone we support or in need of support more accessible to reach us.

description: - ADP LAN Administrator. Experience with Red Hat Linux software, making VAQ-133 the first to have a portable system. logistics capabilities of unparalleled initiative setting up operating systems, software programs, and printers during the squadron gap in IT billeting. Acquired over $30K of computer equipment and classified shredder at no cost to the command freeing OPTAR funds including the acquisition of a $10k system at no cost; making VAQ-133 the first squadron with organic system capabilities. - Responsible for the analysis and reporting of intercepted electronic signals in a tactical environment. - Operated and maintained the Tactical EA-6B Mission Support system (TEAMS). The systems software is used primarily for the mission planning, flight plans, combat scenarios, and as a historical database for radar platforms and for signal identification. - Operated the GALE-LITE and Multi-Advanced Tactical Terminal (MATT). Responsible for collection and analysis of over thousands foreign signals recorded in support of Operation NORTHERN WATCH (ONW), Operation SOUTHERN WATCH (OSW), and Operation IRAQI FREEDOM (OIF). - Provided an accurate database of threat radars and SAM systems to coalition forces in support of OIF. - Used multiple databases, two TEAMS machines, one GALE-LITE system, one MATT system and EA6B aircrew input to create numerous mission reports and databases. - Assistant Intelligence Officer; used multiple ELINT sources to provide over hundreds of briefs to aircrew on active emitters and to make ambiguity determinations with coalition radars. - Earned distinction from Air Force. They awarded us an Air Force ribbon Outstanding Unit Award with Valor. - Developed an accurate Electronic Order of Battle of Iraq, Syria, Iran and Afghanistan. - Managed collection and analysis of ELINT, SIGINT and COMINT for Operation ENDURING FREEDOM.

description: As the SME/Analyst for the Airborne Signals Intelligence Platform (ASIP) at GRSOC, I am responsible for the technical support, analysis of system performance and training of USAF operators on ASIP. Signals and intelligence development on a fast paced operations floor constantly interacting with junior and senior military members and US Air Force civilian staff. As SSO on missions I perform Pre-D and Post-D capture of SOI's in the assigned AOR and analysis/breakdown of captured signals including Type C, Type A and pro-forma. Utilize tools for analysis available through customer sites including WVT, JSP and Martes. Inform chain of command of SOI's through use of tip-offs and KL reporting. Development of Excel charts and pivot tables to assist operators in development of new targets within their assigned AOR. Propose monitoring of new SOI's supported by post mission data and mission data derived from system logs during actual mission activity. Development of geo-location data for new and identified targets utilizing Google Earth and arcGIS. Prepare and deliver briefings to operators, mission supervisors and senior leadership through use of Excel charts and Power Point presentations on a daily basis. Train operators in basic and advanced ASIP theory of operation on an individual basis.

description: Key member of first customer field service team on the ASIP signals system to deploy to a forward operating location providing 100% mission readiness during initial testing and evaluation period. Preflight, post-flight and in-flight engineering support of the ASIP signals platform installed onboard the U-2S aircraft in a fast paced, forward deployed environment. Expert troubleshooting level which allows me to provide recommendations for optimal operation of sensor while on station. Optimization of system capabilities for high band, low band and special signals collection. Weekly interaction with personnel of various DGS's during ground ring evolutions, in-flight updates and post-mission debriefs. Training of customer personnel in operation, use and safety of AN/ASQ-230 (ASIP) system. Repair and replacement of system assets in a location with limited supply availability and logistics support. Outstanding technical writing skills contributed to CFSR team completing major re-writes of system manuals for customer to incorporate in updated manuals. Update of software and scripts on Linux based file server system. Repair and troubleshooting of ATM, electronic file server, classified file server and associated Ethernet wiring. Airborne and ground based network maintenance to support line of sight and beyond line of sight secure communications between AN/ASQ-230 system and ground control stations. Worked various shifts, on call and overtime to ensure system readiness for customer operation and deployment.

description: Maintenance and upkeep of Customs Border Patrol P-3A and P-3B AEW Radar, IFF, Communication, Navigation, ICS, Cryptographic and electrical systems. description: Analyze ground-based, ship borne and unidentified radar emitters for numerous agencies. Accomplishes in-depth all-source analysis to ascertain physical and electronic parameters of the radar and to verify and validate each determination. Represent the local government customer at numerous conferences, working groups, and analytical exchanges in support of the contract. Familiar with all community ELINT tools - particularly strong with MARTES, PASS, SASS, ITAS, DASS/ESP, CED, IEP and CATS toolsuites. Daily Duties - Performed all source detailed analysis of technical data in support of customer contract. Technical Lead for Northrop Grumman. Prepare technical reports; advise collection efforts and site tasking. Ensure database updates are made to include CED as well as other local and national databases. Mentor contractor and government personnel assigned to the customer's Technical ELINT Branch. Trained numerous contractor and government personnel on the use of IEP data and PASS/ITAS, DASS/ESP tool suite. Interactive Processing Specialist (IPS) - Operational support to a real-time processing and reporting system on the Paragon project. Knowledge in computer-based processing systems, analog and digital processors, data processing and communications theory. Working knowledge in FORTRAN and C programming languages as well as SUN/UNIX and CYBER/NOS operating systems. Collected, processed, analyzed and reported new and unusual ELINT emissions. PASS/SASS/ITAS Trainer - Provided demonstrations and OJT to customer personnel ensuring proper use of all analog and digital equipment. RDT/E - Assisted in the test and evaluation of new hardware and software systems for inclusion into PASS/ITAS and future collection/analysis equipment.

summary: I am graduate student working on a Master of Science in Health Sciences with a focus in Management. While studying online, I have had the opportunity to certify to teach English as a foreign language in Manuel Antonio, Costa Rica, teach English in Santiago, Chile, take Spanish Classes in Antigua, Guatemala and Granada, Nicaragua, as well as volunteer with disadvantaged children in Granada. I enjoy studying health care delivery, politics, and policies, improving my writing skills, and learning about management techniques. I also enjoy traveling, learning Spanish, and about different cultures. Studying online has helped me to become self-motivated, independent, and a better communicator. description: Senior intelligence analyst at the Legal Operations Directorate assigned to Combined Joint Interagency Task Force 435. Supervise 11 analysts (military and civilian) who provide all source intelligence and collections support in order to determine who supported Taliban or al-Qaida forces engaged in hostilities against US or its coalition partners. Completed the review of 2493 cases for thoroughness and veracity then disseminated to the proper individuals for use in the Detainee Review Boards. Testified in high visibility board overseen by GEN Jamieson. Also involved in 2 other High Vis cases that General Allen and General Hughber reviewed. As the project manager, established the Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility within the LOD. As a result, insurgents were not released back into the battlefield saving Coalition Forces and local nationals throughout Afghanistan.

description: Deployed in support of United States Special Operations Command (USSOCOM) as parr of a fast paced team tasked with creating all-source, action-oriented intelligence products for SOF teams. Performed rapid data mining and research to create all-source intelligence products, provide input to the Biometric Enabled Watchlist (BEWL), and help standardize TTPs for Identity Intelligence (Biometric Enabled Intelligence/Forensic Enabled Intelligence/DOMEX Enabled Intelligence) with a focus on the Afghanistan counter-insurgency mission. Also supports the war-fighter through identity-centric research on IED networks and provide a path for analytical reach back.

description: Senior intelligence analyst at the Legal Operations Directorate assigned to Combined Joint Interagency Task Force 435. Supervise 11 analysts (military and civilian) who provide all source intelligence and collections support in order to determine who supported Taliban or al-Qaida forces engaged in hostilities against US or its coalition partners. Completed the review of 2493 cases for thoroughness and veracity then disseminated to the proper individuals for use in the Detainee Review Boards. Testified in high visibility board overseen by GEN Jamieson. Also involved in 2 other High Vis cases that General Allen and General Hughber reviewed. As the project manager, established the Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility within the LOD. As a result, insurgents were not released back into the battlefield saving Coalition Forces and local nationals throughout Afghanistan.

description: Communication signals collection and processing operator, signal collection, identification analysis, signal classification, target identification and various report formats using various types of test and measuring instruments, wireless/cellular communications such as FDMA, TDMA, CDMA, adaptive high frequency automatic links, basics of optical communication and use of MARTES software. Operating the Joint Maritime command Information System (JMCIS), Command Cryptologic workstation (CCWS) and cryptologic collection systems comprised of radio receivers, recorders, computer terminals and peripheral equipment. Perform mobile cryptolgic collection duties. Operates the SSEE Increment E (AN/SSQ-137) and all MCS-21 cryptologic system installed on U.S. Naval Combatants, in order to provide cryptologic combat support to warfare commanders. Controlling flow of messages and information. Adminisrative and clerical duties involving classified materials. Minor to moderate levels of installation, servicing, and repair of electronic and electromechanical equipment. Operation and maintenance of telecommunications equipment and AIS networking and information management. Operating signals collection equipment, systems, and antennas for analysis in identifying essential elements of information. Drafting Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) reports and executing radio direction finding (RDF) operation. Maintaining cryptologic databases to aid in target development. Supervising signals collection, analysis, reporting, SI communications and signals intelligence personnel. Allocating Signals Intelligence resources and adjusting tasking requirements. Drafting cryptologic mission reports and emergency action plans. Condicting quality control and release of time-sensetive reports. Complying with classified information storage, transportation and protection requirements. Demonstrating in-depth knowledge of UNIX operating systems, advanced modulation techniques, digital communications analysis.
